Giant pandas are said to have been around during the time of dinosaurs and regarded as a "national gem" of China.
Currently more than 1,500 giant pandas live wild in China, according to a survey by the State Forestry Administration.
Giant pandas, said to have been around during the time of dinosaurs, are cited as a "national gem" of China.
Giant pandas will not eat the bamboo after it blooms and it takes 10 years for a new supply to grow.
To protect the animal species, dubbed a "national gem," China has set up 33 nature reserves with a combined area of 1.6 million hectares.
